<paragraph id="8B94DB56FFD5FFBEFF49F8D3B1CC9826" blockId="4.[166,777,1898,2091]" lastBlockId="4.[813,1420,1398,1560]" pageId="4" pageNumber="989">
<emphasis id="B95F0744FFD5FFBEFF49F8D3B34C99BC" bold="true" box="[168,327,1898,1922]" pageId="4" pageNumber="989">Identification.</emphasis>
Males examined were easily identified as 
<taxonomicName id="4C2BA0D5FFD5FFBEFF49F834B310999A" authorityName="Drake &amp; Harris" authorityYear="1933" box="[168,283,1932,1956]" class="Insecta" family="Gerridae" genus="Limnogonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="989" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aduncus">
<emphasis id="B95F0744FFD5FFBEFF49F834B310999A" box="[168,283,1932,1956]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="989">L. aduncus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on the shape of abdominal segment VIII, which has a small, downward curving, apical projection on the ventral surface (
<figureCitation id="1310C7D3FFD5FFBEFE7CF876B3D499D6" box="[413,479,1999,2024]" captionStart="Figures 8–10" captionStartId="4.[813,884,1271,1291]" captionTargetBox="[168,1414,160,1277]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figures 8–10. Limnogonus aduncus. 8. Apterous male, dorsal view. 9. Male, apex of abdomen, lateral view. 10. Female, apex of abdomen, lateral view." pageId="4" pageNumber="989">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Females are more difficult to identify but could be recognized by the antennomere I longer than the head width including the eyes, dorsal portion of the mesopleura dark with a transversal light stripe in the middle, last abdominal laterotergite clearly projected posteriorly (
<figureCitation id="1310C7D3FFD5FFBEFBFEFA02B67A9BED" box="[1055,1137,1467,1491]" captionStart="Figures 8–10" captionStartId="4.[813,884,1271,1291]" captionTargetBox="[168,1414,160,1277]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Figures 8–10. Limnogonus aduncus. 8. Apterous male, dorsal view. 9. Male, apex of abdomen, lateral view. 10. Female, apex of abdomen, lateral view." pageId="4" pageNumber="989">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
), and posterior margin of abdominal sternite VII sharply projected in the middle (
<bibRefCitation id="EFBAA6A7FFD5FFBEFCD5F9B9B1B79826" author="Nieser N" box="[820,956,1536,1560]" pageId="4" pageNumber="989" pagination="94 - 138" refId="ref16714" refString="Nieser N (1970) Gerridae of Suriname and the Amazon with additional records of other neotropical species. Studies on the Fauna of Suriname and other Guyanas 12 (47): 94 - 138." type="journal article" year="1970">Nieser 1970</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
